# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cloud-security-posture-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Cloud computing and storage provide users with the capability to store and process their data in third-party data centers.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Organizations use the cloud in a variety of service models (e.g., SaaS, PaaS, IaaS) and deployment models (private, public, hybrid, and community).
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Security concerns associated with cloud computing are typically divided into issues faced by cloud providers and those faced by their customers.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] The responsibility is shared and is often described in a vendor's "shared responsibility model".
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] The provider must secure its infrastructure, while customers must secure their applications, identities, and configuration settings.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Analyses of large-scale cloud incidents indicate that many breaches result from misconfigurations and long-unremediated exposures rather than solely from zero-day vulnerabilities.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] When an organization stores data or hosts applications on the public cloud, it loses physical access to the hardware.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] As a result, potentially sensitive data may be at risk from insider attacks.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] According to a 2010 Cloud Security Alliance report, insider attacks rank among the top threats in cloud computing.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service providers must ensure that thorough background checks are conducted for employees with physical access to data centers.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] To conserve resources and reduce cost, cloud providers often store multiple customers' data on the same server.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] As a result, one user's private data might be viewable by another without proper isolation.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Providers implement data isolation and logical segregation to mitigate these risks.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] The extensive use of virtualization in cloud infrastructure brings unique security concerns.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Virtualization introduces an additional layer—the hypervisor—that must be secured and correctly configured.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] A compromise of the hypervisor management system can impact an entire data center.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security architecture is effective only if the correct defensive implementations are in place.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] An efficient cloud security architecture should recognize the issues that will arise with security management and follow all the best practices, procedures, and guidelines to ensure a secure cloud environment.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Security management addresses these issues with security controls.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] These controls protect cloud environments and are put in place to safeguard any weaknesses in the system and reduce the effect of an attack.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Administrative mechanisms intended to reduce attacks by informing attackers of consequences.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Controls designed to reduce vulnerabilities and prevent unauthorized access.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Controls that detect and respond to security events.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Includes monitoring, SIEM, IDS/IPS, malware detection.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Controls that reduce the impact of an incident and restore systems.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security engineering is characterized by the security layers, plan, design, programming, and best practices that exist inside a cloud security arrangement.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security engineering requires the composed and visual model (design and UI) to be characterized by the tasks inside the Cloud.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] This cloud security engineering process includes such things as access to the executives, techniques, and controls to ensure applications and information.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] It also includes ways to deal with and keep up with permeability, consistency, danger stance, and by and large security.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Processes for imparting security standards into cloud administrations and activities assume an approach that fulfills consistent guidelines and essential foundation security parts.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Though the idea of cloud computing is not new, organizations are increasingly adopting it because of its flexible scalability, relative trustability, and cost-effectiveness of services.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] However, despite its rapid adoption in some sectors and disciplines, research and statistics indicate that security-related pitfalls remain a major barrier to its full adoption.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] It is generally recommended that information security controls be selected and implemented in proportion to the risks, typically by assessing the threats, vulnerabilities and impacts.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security concerns can be grouped in various ways; Gartner identified seven, while the Cloud Security Alliance identified twelve areas of concern.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Cloud access security brokers (CASBs) are software that sits between cloud users and cloud applications to provide visibility into cloud application usage, data protection and governance to monitor all activity and enforce security policies.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Any service without a "hardened" environment is considered a "soft" target.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Virtual servers should be protected just like a physical server against data leakage, malware, and exploited vulnerabilities.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] "Data loss or leakage represents 24.6 % and cloud-related malware 3.4 % of threats causing cloud outages".
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Every enterprise will have its own identity management system to control access to information and computing resources.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Cloud providers either integrate the customer's identity management system into their own infrastructure, using federation or SSO technology or a biometric-based identification system, or provide an identity management system of their own.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service providers physically secure the IT hardware (servers, routers, cables etc.) against unauthorized access, interference, theft, fire, flood etc., and ensure that essential supplies (such as electricity) are sufficiently robust to minimise the possibility of disruption.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Various information security concerns relating to personnel involved in cloud services are typically handled through screening, security-awareness training, and role-based access controls.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Providers ensure that all critical data (credit-card numbers, for example) are masked or encrypted and that only authorised users have access to data in its entirety.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Moreover, digital identities and credentials must be protected as must any data that the provider collects or produces about customer activity in the cloud.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Penetration testing is the process of performing offensive security tests on a system, service, or computer network to find security weaknesses in it.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Since the cloud is a shared environment with other customers or tenants, following penetration-testing rules of engagement step-by-step is a mandatory requirement.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Scanning and penetration-testing from inside or outside the cloud should be authorised by the cloud provider.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Scanning the cloud from outside and inside using free or commercial tools is crucial.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Without a hardened environment, your service is considered a soft target.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Virtual servers should be hardened just like a physical server against data leakage, malware, and exploited vulnerabilities.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Privacy legislation often varies by country.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] By having information stored via the cloud it is difficult to determine under which jurisdiction the data falls.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Trans-border clouds are popular given that the largest companies transcend several countries.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Legal dilemmas from the ambiguity of the cloud refer to how there is a difference in data-sharing law between and inside organisations.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Due to the autonomous nature of the cloud, consumers are often given management interfaces to monitor their databases.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] By having controls in one central location and by having the interface be easily accessible for user convenience, there is a possibility that a single actor could gain access to the cloud's management interface; giving them control over much of the system.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] The cloud's use of resource pooling means memory or storage resources may be recycled to another user.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] It is possible for current users to access information left by previous ones.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Cloud services require internet connectivity and use internet protocols, making them subject to attacks such as man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Furthermore, heavy reliance on internet connectivity means service disruptions or outages can cut off users entirely.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] As encryption algorithms age, vulnerabilities arise.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Cloud providers must stay current with encryption standards and transition older systems before they become compromised.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Some advanced encryption algorithms applied to cloud computing increase the protection of privacy.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] In a practice called crypto-shredding, encryption keys can be deleted when data is no longer used.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Attribute-based encryption is a form of public-key encryption in which the user's secret key and the ciphertext depend on attributes (e.g., the country the user lives in, or their subscription type).
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] In such systems, access to decryption depends not simply on identity but on attributes.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Some of the strengths of ABE are that it bypasses the need for explicit key sharing (as in traditional PKI) and identity-based encryption (IBE).
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] However, ABE suffers from key-redistribution complexity: since decryption keys depend on attributes rather than identities, malicious users might leak attribute information, enabling unauthorized access.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] In CP-ABE, the encryptor controls the access policy for the ciphertext.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] The process includes Setup, Encrypt, KeyGen, and Decrypt algorithms; the encryptor defines an access structure that must match a user's attributes before decryption is allowed.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] In KP-ABE, the sender encrypts under a set of attributes, and the user's private key is issued to match a policy describing which ciphertexts they may decrypt.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] KP-ABE shifts access-control responsibility partially to the key-issuer rather than the encryptor.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] While it provides flexibility, the policy disclosure may weaken privacy guarantees.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Fully Homomorphic Encryption allows arbitrary computation on ciphertext without decryption.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] It is emerging as a high-security option for cloud environments, including voting systems.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] While promising, it remains largely experimental.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Searchable encryption enables secure search on encrypted data.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] It has symmetric and public-key variants.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] While it supports functionality over encrypted data, it introduces extra attack surfaces, especially when attribute indexing is involved.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Numerous laws and regulations govern the storage and use of data.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Similar standards exist in other jurisdictions (e.g., Singapore's Multi-Tier Cloud Security Standard).
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Similar laws may apply in different legal jurisdictions and may differ markedly from those in the US.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service users must often understand the legal and regulatory differences between the jurisdictions.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] For example, data stored by a cloud service provider (CSP) may be located in, say, Singapore and mirrored in the US.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] plans in place to ensure service continuity and data protection.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] In addition to the requirements on customers, data centers used by cloud providers may be subject to additional compliance obligations.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Using a cloud service provider (CSP) can lead to extra security concerns around data jurisdiction since customer or tenant data may not remain in the same location or provider's cloud.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] These issues are typically addressed in service-level agreements (SLAs).
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing-security] Legal issues may also include records-keeping requirements in the public sector, where agencies must retain and make available electronic records in a specific fashion.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] In 2011, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) identified five "essential characteristics" for cloud systems.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] By 2023, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) had expanded and refined the list.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] The history of cloud computing extends to the 1960s, with the initial concepts of time-sharing becoming popularized via remote job entry (RJE).
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] The "data center" model, where users submitted jobs to operators to run on mainframes, was predominantly used during this era.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] This period saw broad experimentation with making large-scale computing power more accessible through time-sharing, while optimizing infrastructure, platforms, and applications to improve efficiency for end users.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] The "cloud" metaphor for virtualized services dates to 1994, when it was used by General Magic for the universe of "places" that mobile agents in the Telescript environment could "go".
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] The metaphor is credited to David Hoffman, a General Magic communications specialist, based on its long-standing use in networking and telecom.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] The expression *cloud computing* became more widely known in 1996 when Compaq Computer Corporation drew up a business plan for future computing and the Internet.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] The company's ambition was to supercharge sales with "cloud computing-enabled applications".
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] The business plan foresaw that online consumer file storage would likely be commercially successful.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] As a result, Compaq decided to sell server hardware to internet service providers.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] In the 2000s, the application of cloud computing began to take shape with the establishment of Amazon Web Services (AWS) in 2002, which allowed developers to build applications independently.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] In 2006 Amazon Simple Storage Service, known as Amazon S3, and the Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) were released.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] In 2008 NASA's development of the first open-source software for deploying private and hybrid clouds.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] The following decade saw the launch of various cloud services.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] In 2010, Microsoft launched Microsoft Azure, and Rackspace Hosting and NASA initiated an open-source cloud-software project, OpenStack.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] IBM introduced the IBM SmartCloud framework in 2011, and Oracle announced the Oracle Cloud in 2012.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] In December 2019, Amazon launched AWS Outposts, a service that extends AWS infrastructure, services, APIs, and tools to customer data centers, co-location spaces, or on-premises facilities.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud computing can shorten time to market by offering pre-configured tools, scalable resources, and managed services, allowing users to focus on core business value rather than maintaining infrastructure.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms can enable organizations and individuals to reduce upfront capital expenditures on physical infrastructure by shifting to an operational expenditure model, where costs scale with usage.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms also offer managed services and tools, such as artificial intelligence, data analytics, and machine learning, which might otherwise require significant in-house expertise and infrastructure investment.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] While cloud computing can offer cost advantages through effective resource optimization, organizations often face challenges such as unused resources, inefficient configurations, and hidden costs without proper oversight and governance.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Many cloud platforms provide cost management tools, such as AWS Cost Explorer and Azure Cost Management, and frameworks like FinOps have emerged to standardize financial operations in the cloud.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud computing also facilitates collaboration, remote work, and global service delivery by enabling secure access to data and applications from any location with an internet connection.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud providers offer various redundancy options for core services, such as managed storage and managed databases, though redundancy configurations often vary by service tier.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Advanced redundancy strategies, such as cross-region replication or failover systems, typically require explicit configuration and may incur additional costs or licensing fees.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud environments operate under a shared responsibility model, where providers are typically responsible for infrastructure security, physical hardware, and software updates, while customers are accountable for data encryption, identity and access management (IAM), and application-level security.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] The decision to adopt cloud computing or maintain on-premises infrastructure depends on factors such as scalability, cost structure, latency requirements, regulatory constraints, and infrastructure customization.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Organizations with variable or unpredictable workloads, limited capital for upfront investments, or a focus on rapid scalability benefit from cloud adoption.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Startups, SaaS companies, and e-commerce platforms often prefer the pay-as-you-go operational expenditure (OpEx) model of cloud infrastructure.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies prioritizing global accessibility, remote workforce enablement, disaster recovery, and leveraging advanced services such as AI/ML and analytics are well-suited for the cloud.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] In recent years, some cloud providers have started offering specialized services for high-performance computing and low-latency applications, addressing some use cases previously exclusive to on-premises setups.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] On the other hand, organizations with strict regulatory requirements, highly predictable workloads, or reliance on deeply integrated legacy systems may find cloud infrastructure less suitable.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Businesses in industries like defense, government, or those handling highly sensitive data often favor on-premises setups for greater control and data sovereignty.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies with ultra-low latency requirements, such as high-frequency trading (HFT) firms, rely on custom hardware (e.g., FPGAs) and physical proximity to exchanges, which most cloud providers cannot fully replicate despite recent advancements.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Similarly, tech giants like Google, Meta, and Amazon build their own data centers due to economies of scale, predictable workloads, and the ability to customize hardware and network infrastructure for optimal efficiency.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] However, these companies also use cloud services selectively for certain workloads and applications where it aligns with their operational needs.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] In practice, many organizations are increasingly adopting hybrid cloud architectures, combining on-premises infrastructure with cloud services.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] This approach allows businesses to balance scalability, cost-effectiveness, and control, offering the benefits of both deployment models while mitigating their respective limitations.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] One of the primary challenges of cloud computing, compared with traditional on-premises systems, is maintaining data security and privacy.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud users entrust their sensitive data to third-party providers, who may not have adequate measures to protect it from unauthorized access, breaches, or leaks.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud users also face compliance risks if they have to adhere to certain regulations or standards regarding data protection, such as GDPR or HIPAA.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Another challenge of cloud computing is reduced visibility and control.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud users may not have full insight into how their cloud resources are managed, configured, or optimized by their providers.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] They may also have limited ability to customize or modify their cloud services according to their specific needs or preferences.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Complete understanding of all technology may be impossible, especially given the scale, complexity, and deliberate opacity of contemporary systems; however, there is a need for understanding complex technologies and their interconnections to have power and agency within them.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] The metaphor of the cloud can be seen as problematic as cloud computing retains the aura of something noumenal and numinous; it is something experienced without precisely understanding what it is or how it works.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Additionally, cloud migration is a significant challenge.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] This process involves transferring data, applications, or workloads from one cloud environment to another, or from on-premises infrastructure to the cloud.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud migration can be complicated, time-consuming, and expensive, particularly when there are compatibility issues between different cloud platforms or architectures.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] If not carefully planned and executed, cloud migration can lead to downtime, reduced performance, or even data loss.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Applications hosted in the cloud are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing, a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] In a report by Gartner, a survey of 200 IT leaders revealed that 69% experienced budget overruns in their organizations' cloud expenditures during 2023.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Conversely, 31% of IT leaders whose organizations stayed within budget attributed their success to accurate forecasting and budgeting, proactive monitoring of spending, and effective optimization.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] The 2024 Flexera State of Cloud Report identifies the top cloud challenges as managing cloud spend, followed by security concerns and lack of expertise.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Public cloud expenditures exceeded budgeted amounts by an average of 15%.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] The report also reveals that cost savings is the top cloud initiative for 60% of respondents.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Furthermore, 65% measure cloud progress through cost savings, while 42% prioritize shorter time-to-market, indicating that cloud's promise of accelerated deployment is often overshadowed by cost concerns.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Typically, cloud providers' Service Level Agreements (SLAs) do not encompass all forms of service interruptions.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Exclusions typically include planned maintenance, downtime resulting from external factors such as network issues, human errors, like misconfigurations, natural disasters, force majeure events, or security breaches.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Typically, customers bear the responsibility of monitoring SLA compliance and must file claims for any unmet SLAs within a designated timeframe.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Customers should be aware of how deviations from SLAs are calculated, as these parameters may vary by service.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] These requirements can place a considerable burden on customers.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Additionally, SLA percentages and conditions can differ across various services within the same provider, with some services lacking any SLA altogether.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] In cases of service interruptions due to hardware failures in the cloud provider, the company typically does not offer monetary compensation.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Instead, eligible users may receive credits as outlined in the corresponding SLA.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud computing abstractions aim to simplify resource management, but leaky abstractions can expose underlying complexities.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] These variations in abstraction quality depend on the cloud vendor, service and architecture.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Mitigating leaky abstractions requires users to understand the implementation details and limitations of the cloud services they utilize.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Service lock-in within the same vendor occurs when a customer becomes dependent on specific services within a cloud vendor, making it challenging to switch to alternative services within the same vendor when their needs change.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud computing poses privacy concerns because the service provider can access the data that is in the cloud at any time.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] It could accidentally or deliberately alter or delete information.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Many cloud providers can share information with third parties if necessary for purposes of law and order without a warrant.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] That is permitted in their privacy policies, which users must agree to before they start using cloud services.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Solutions to privacy include policy and legislation as well as end-users' choices for how data is stored.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Users can encrypt data that is processed or stored within the cloud to prevent unauthorized access.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Identity management systems can also provide practical solutions to privacy concerns in cloud computing.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] These systems distinguish between authorized and unauthorized users and determine the amount of data that is accessible to each entity.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] The systems work by creating and describing identities, recording activities, and getting rid of unused identities.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] According to the Cloud Security Alliance, the top three threats in the cloud are *Insecure Interfaces and APIs*, *Data Loss & Leakage*, and *Hardware Failure*—which accounted for 29%, 25% and 10% of all cloud security outages respectively.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Together, these form shared technology vulnerabilities.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] In a cloud provider platform being shared by different users, there may be a possibility that information belonging to different customers resides on the same data server.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Additionally, Eugene Schultz, chief technology officer at Emagined Security, said that hackers are spending substantial time and effort looking for ways to penetrate the cloud.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] "There are some real Achilles' heels in the cloud infrastructure that are making big holes for the bad guys to get into".
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Because data from hundreds or thousands of companies can be stored on large cloud servers, hackers can theoretically gain control of huge stores of information through a single attack—a process he called "hyperjacking".
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Some examples of this include the Dropbox security breach, and iCloud 2014 leak.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Dropbox had been breached in October 2014, having over seven million of its users passwords stolen by hackers in an effort to get monetary value from it by Bitcoins (BTC).
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] By having these passwords, they are able to read private data as well as have this data be indexed by search engines (making the information public).
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] There is the problem of legal ownership of the data (If a user stores some data in the cloud, can the cloud provider profit from it?).
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Many Terms of Service agreements are silent on the question of ownership.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Physical control of the computer equipment (private cloud) is more secure than having the equipment off-site and under someone else's control (public cloud).
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] This delivers great incentive to public cloud computing service providers to prioritize building and maintaining strong management of secure services.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Some small businesses that do not have expertise in IT security could find that it is more secure for them to use a public cloud.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] There is the risk that end users do not understand the issues involved when signing on to a cloud service (persons sometimes do not read the many pages of the terms of service agreement, and just click "Accept" without reading).
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] This is important now that cloud computing is common and required for some services to work, for example for an intelligent personal assistant (Apple's Siri or Google Assistant).
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Fundamentally, private cloud is seen as more secure with higher levels of control for the owner, however public cloud is seen to be more flexible and requires less time and money investment from the user.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] The attacks that can be made on cloud computing systems include man-in-the middle attacks, phishing attacks, authentication attacks, and malware attacks.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] One of the largest threats is considered to be malware attacks, such as Trojan horses.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Recent research conducted in 2022 has revealed that the Trojan horse injection method is a serious problem with harmful impacts on cloud computing systems.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] The CLOUD Act allows United States authorities to request data from cloud providers, and courts can impose nondisclosure requirements preventing providers from notifying affected users.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] This framework is in legal tension with Article 48 of the European General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which restricts the transfer of personal data in response to foreign court or administrative orders unless based on an international agreement.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] As a result, cloud service providers operating in both Europe and the U.S. may face competing legal obligations.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Donohue writing for the *Harvard Journal of Law and Public Policy*, cloud service providers also fall within the broader category of service providers subject to Section 702 of the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act (FISA), which has had documented effects on cloud providers and their customers.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] The National Institute of Standards and Technology recognized three cloud service models in 2011: Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS).
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) later identified additional models in 2023, including "Network as a Service", "Communications as a Service", "Compute as a Service", and "Data Storage as a Service".
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Infrastructure as a service (IaaS) refers to online services that provide high-level APIs used to abstract various low-level details of underlying network infrastructure like physical computing resources, location, data partitioning, scaling, security, backup, etc.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] A hypervisor runs the virtual machines as guests.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Pools of hypervisors within the cloud operational system can support large numbers of virtual machines and the ability to scale services up and down according to customers' varying requirements.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Linux containers run in isolated partitions of a single Linux kernel running directly on the physical hardware.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Linux cgroups and namespaces are the underlying Linux kernel technologies used to isolate, secure and manage the containers.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] The use of containers offers higher performance than virtualization because there is no hypervisor overhead.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] IaaS clouds often offer additional resources such as a virtual-machine disk-image library, raw block storage, file or object storage, firewalls, load balancers, IP addresses, virtual local area networks (VLANs), and software bundles.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] The NIST's definition of cloud computing describes IaaS as "where the consumer is able to deploy and run arbitrary software, which can include operating systems and applications.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] IaaS-cloud providers supply these resources on-demand from their large pools of equipment installed in data centers.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] For wide-area connectivity, customers can use either the Internet or carrier clouds (dedicated virtual private networks).
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] To deploy their applications, cloud users install operating-system images and their application software on the cloud infrastructure.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] In this model, the cloud user patches and maintains the operating systems and the application software.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud providers typically bill IaaS services on a utility computing basis: cost reflects the number of resources allocated and consumed.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] PaaS vendors offer a development environment to application developers.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] The provider typically develops toolkit and standards for development and channels for distribution and payment.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] In the PaaS models, cloud providers deliver a computing platform, typically including an operating system, programming-language execution environment, database, and the web server.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Application developers develop and run their software on a cloud platform instead of directly buying and managing the underlying hardware and software layers.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] With some PaaS, the underlying computer and storage resources scale automatically to match application demand so that the cloud user does not have to allocate resources manually.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Some integration and data management providers also use specialized applications of PaaS as delivery models for data.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Examples include **iPaaS (Integration Platform as a Service)** and **dPaaS (Data Platform as a Service)**. iPaaS enables customers to develop, execute and govern integration flows.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Under the iPaaS integration model, customers drive the development and deployment of integrations without installing or managing any hardware or middleware. dPaaS delivers integration—and data-management—products as a fully managed service.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Under the dPaaS model, the PaaS provider, not the customer, manages the development and execution of programs by building data applications for the customer. dPaaS users access data through data-visualization tools.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] In the software as a service (SaaS) model, users gain access to application software and databases.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud providers manage the infrastructure and platforms that run the applications.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] SaaS is sometimes referred to as "on-demand software" and is usually priced on a pay-per-use basis or using a subscription fee.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] In the SaaS model, cloud providers install and operate application software in the cloud and cloud users access the software from cloud clients.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud users do not manage the cloud infrastructure and platform where the application runs.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] This eliminates the need to install and run the application on the cloud user's own computers, which simplifies maintenance and support.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud applications differ from other applications in their scalability—which can be achieved by cloning tasks onto multiple virtual machines at run-time to meet changing work demand.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Load balancers distribute the work over the set of virtual machines.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] This process is transparent to the cloud user, who sees only a single access-point.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] To accommodate a large number of cloud users, cloud applications can be *multitenant*, meaning that any machine may serve more than one cloud-user organization.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] The pricing model for SaaS applications is typically a monthly or yearly flat fee per user, so prices become scalable and adjustable if users are added or removed at any point.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Proponents claim that SaaS gives a business the potential to reduce IT operational costs by outsourcing hardware and software maintenance and support to the cloud provider.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] This enables the business to reallocate IT operations costs away from hardware/software spending and from personnel expenses, towards meeting other goals.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] In addition, with applications hosted centrally, updates can be released without the need for users to install new software.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] One drawback of SaaS comes with storing the users' data on the cloud provider's server.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] As a result, there could be unauthorized access to the data.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Examples of applications offered as SaaS are games and productivity software like Google Docs and Office Online.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] SaaS applications may be integrated with cloud storage or File hosting services, which is the case with Google Docs being integrated with Google Drive, and Office Online being integrated with OneDrive.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Serverless computing allows customers to use various cloud capabilities without the need to provision, deploy, or manage hardware or software resources, apart from providing their application code or data.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] ISO/IEC 22123-2:2023 classifies serverless alongside Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS) under the broader category of cloud service categories.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Notably, while ISO refers to these classifications as cloud service categories, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) refers to them as service models.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] "A cloud deployment model represents the way in which cloud computing can be organized based on the control and sharing of physical or virtual resources." Cloud deployment models define the fundamental patterns of interaction between cloud customers and cloud providers.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] They do not detail implementation specifics or the configuration of resources.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Private cloud is cloud infrastructure operated solely for a single organization, whether managed internally or by a third party, and hosted either internally or externally.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Undertaking a private cloud project requires significant engagement to virtualize the business environment, and requires the organization to reevaluate decisions about existing resources.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] It can improve business, but every step in the project raises security issues that must be addressed to prevent serious vulnerabilities.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Self-run data centers are generally capital intensive.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] They have a significant physical footprint, requiring allocations of space, hardware, and environmental controls.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] These assets have to be refreshed periodically, resulting in additional capital expenditures.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] They have attracted criticism because users "still have to buy, build, and manage them" and thus do not benefit from less hands-on management, essentially "[lacking] the economic model that makes cloud computing such an intriguing concept".
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud services are considered "public" when they are delivered over the public Internet, and they may be offered as a paid subscription, or free of charge.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Architecturally, there are few differences between public- and private-cloud services, but security concerns increase substantially when services (applications, storage, and other resources) are shared by multiple customers.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Most public-cloud providers offer direct-connection services that allow customers to securely link their legacy data centers to their cloud-resident applications.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Several factors like the functionality of the solutions, cost, integrational and organizational aspects as well as safety & security are influencing the decision of enterprises and organizations to choose a public cloud or on-premises solution.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Varied use cases for hybrid cloud composition exist.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] For example, an organization may store sensitive client data in house on a private cloud application, but interconnect that application to a business intelligence application provided on a public cloud as a software service.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] This example of hybrid cloud extends the capabilities of the enterprise to deliver a specific business service through the addition of externally available public cloud services.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Hybrid cloud adoption depends on a number of factors such as data security and compliance requirements, level of control needed over data, and the applications an organization uses.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Another example of hybrid cloud is one where IT organizations use public cloud computing resources to meet temporary capacity needs that can not be met by the private cloud.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] This capability enables hybrid clouds to employ cloud bursting for scaling across clouds.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting is an application deployment model in which an application runs in a private cloud or data center and "bursts" to a public cloud when the demand for computing capacity increases.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] A primary advantage of cloud bursting and a hybrid cloud model is that an organization pays for extra compute resources only when they are needed.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting enables data centers to create an in-house IT infrastructure that supports average workloads, and use cloud resources from public or private clouds, during spikes in processing demands.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] As a result, only a portion of the potential cost savings of cloud computing is achieved.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] According to ISO/IEC 22123-1: "multi-cloud is a cloud deployment model in which a customer uses public cloud services provided by two or more cloud service providers".
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Poly cloud refers to the use of multiple public clouds for the purpose of leveraging specific services that each provider offers.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] It differs from Multi cloud in that it is not designed to increase flexibility or mitigate against failures but is rather used to allow an organization to achieve more than could be done with a single provider.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] According to International Data Corporation (IDC), global spending on cloud computing services has reached $706 billion and is expected to reach $1.3 trillion by 2025.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Gartner estimated that global public cloud services end-user spending would reach $600 billion by 2023.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] According to a McKinsey & Company report, cloud cost-optimization levers and value-oriented business use cases foresee more than $1 trillion in run-rate EBITDA across Fortune 500 companies as up for grabs in 2030.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] In 2022, more than $1.3 trillion in enterprise IT spending was at stake from the shift to the cloud, growing to almost $1.8 trillion in 2025, according to Gartner.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] The *Communication* set out a series of "digital agenda actions" which the Commission proposed to undertake in order to support the development of a fair and effective market for cloud computing services.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] As of 2025, the three largest cloud computing providers by market share, commonly referred to as hyperscalers, are Amazon Web Services (AWS), Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] These companies dominate the global cloud market due to their extensive infrastructure, broad service offerings, and scalability.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] In recent years, organizations have increasingly adopted alternative cloud providers, which offer specialized services that distinguish them from hyperscalers.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Alternative cloud providers are often part of multi-cloud strategies, where organizations use multiple cloud services—both from hyperscalers and specialized providers—to optimize performance, compliance, and cost efficiency.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] However, they do not necessarily serve as direct replacements for hyperscalers, as their offerings are typically more specialized.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] The goal of cloud computing is to allow users to take benefit from all of these technologies, without the need for deep knowledge about or expertise with each one of them.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] The cloud aims to cut costs and helps the users focus on their core business instead of being impeded by IT obstacles.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] The main enabling technology for cloud computing is virtualization.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Virtualization software separates a physical computing device into one or more "virtual" devices, each of which can be easily used and managed to perform computing tasks.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] With operating system-level virtualization essentially creating a scalable system of multiple independent computing devices, idle computing resources can be allocated and used more efficiently.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Virtualization provides the agility required to speed up IT operations and reduces cost by increasing infrastructure utilization.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Autonomic computing automates the process through which the user can provision resources on-demand.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] By minimizing user involvement, automation speeds up the process, reduces labor costs and reduces the possibility of human errors.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud computing uses concepts from utility computing to provide metrics for the services used.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud computing attempts to address QoS (quality of service) and reliability problems of other grid computing models.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] CM applied over the lifecycle of a system provides visibility and control of its performance, functional, and physical attributes.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] CM verifies that a system performs as intended, and is documented in sufficient detail to support its projected life cycle.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] The CM process facilitates orderly management of system information and system changes for purposes such as to revise capability; improve performance, reliability, or maintainability; extend life; reduce costs; reduce risk and liability; or correct defects.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] The relatively minimal cost of implementing CM is returned manyfold in cost avoidance.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] The lack of CM (or its ineffectual implementation) can be very expensive and sometimes can have such catastrophic consequences such as failure of equipment or loss of life.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] CM emphasizes the functional relation between parts, subsystems, and systems for effectively controlling system change.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] It helps to verify that proposed changes are systematically considered to minimize adverse effects.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] Changes to the system are proposed, evaluated, and implemented using a standardized, systematic approach that ensures consistency, and proposed changes are evaluated in terms of their anticipated impact on the entire system.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] CM verifies that changes are carried out as specified and that documentation of items and systems reflects their true configuration.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] A complete CM program includes provisions for the storing, tracking, and updating of all system information on a component, subsystem, and system basis.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] A structured CM program ensures that documentation (e.g., requirements, design, test, and acceptance documentation) for items is accurate and consistent with the actual physical design of the item.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] In many cases, without CM, the documentation exists but is not consistent with the item itself.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] For this reason, engineers, contractors, and management are frequently forced to develop documentation reflecting the actual status of the item before they can proceed with a change.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] This reverse engineering process is wasteful in terms of human and other resources and can be minimized or eliminated using CM.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] Configuration management originated in the United States Department of Defense in the 1950s as a technical management discipline for hardware material items—and it is now a standard practice in virtually every industry.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] The CM process became its own technical discipline in the late 1960s when the DoD developed a series of military standards called the "480 series" (i.e., MIL-STD-480, MIL-STD-481 and MIL-STD-483) that were subsequently issued in the 1970s.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] This marked the beginning of what has now evolved into the most widely distributed and accepted standard on CM, ANSI–EIA–649–1998.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] Many of these functions and models have redefined CM from its traditional holistic approach to technical management.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] Some treat CM as being similar to a librarian activity and break out change control or change management as a separate or standalone discipline.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] CM is the practice of handling changes systematically so that a system maintains its integrity over time.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] CM implements the policies, procedures, techniques, and tools that manage, evaluate proposed changes, track change status, and maintain an inventory of system and support documents as the system changes.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] CM programs and plans provide technical and administrative direction to the development and implementation of the procedures, functions, services, tools, processes, and resources required to successfully develop and support a complex system.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] During system development, CM allows program management to track requirements throughout the life-cycle through acceptance and operations and maintenance.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] As changes inevitably occur in the requirements and design, they must be approved and documented, creating an accurate record of the system status.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] Ideally the CM process is applied throughout the system life cycle.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] Many professionals mix up or get confused with Asset management (AM, see also ISO/IEC 19770), where it inventories the assets on hand.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] The key difference between CM and AM is that the former does not manage the financial accounting aspect but the service that the system supports or in other words, that the latter (AM) is trying to realize value from an IT asset.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] The CM process for both hardware and software configuration items comprises five distinct disciplines as established in the MIL–HDBK–61A and in ANSI/EIA-649.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] Members of an organization interested in applying a standard change-management process will employ these disciplines as policies and procedures for establishing baselines, manage and control change, and monitor and assess the effectiveness and correctness of progress.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] The IEEE 12207 process IEEE 12207.2 also has these activities and adds "Release management and delivery".
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] Configuration Identification (CI): consists of setting and maintaining baselines, which define the system or subsystem architecture, components, and any developments at any point in time.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] It is the basis by which changes to any part of a system are identified, documented, and later tracked through design, development, testing, and final delivery.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] CI incrementally establishes and maintains the definitive current basis for Configuration Status Accounting (CSA) of a system and its configuration items (CIs) throughout their life cycle (development, production, deployment, and operational support) until disposal.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] Configuration Control: includes the evaluation of all change-requests and change-proposals, and their subsequent approval or disapproval.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] It covers the process of controlling modifications to the system's design, hardware, firmware, software, and documentation.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] Configuration Status Accounting: includes the process of recording and reporting configuration item descriptions (e.g., hardware, software, firmware, etc.) and all departures from the baseline during design and production.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] In the event of suspected problems, operators can quickly verify baseline configuration and approved modifications.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] Configuration Verification and Audit: an independent review of hardware and software for the purpose of assessing compliance with established performance requirements, commercial and appropriate military standards, and functional, allocated, and product baselines.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] Configuration audits verify that the system and subsystem configuration documentation complies with the functional and physical performance characteristics before acceptance into an architectural baseline.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] The software configuration management (SCM) process is looked upon by practitioners as the best solution to handling changes in software projects.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] It identifies the functional and physical attributes of software at various points in time, and performs systematic control of changes to the identified attributes for the purpose of maintaining software integrity and traceability throughout the software development life cycle.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] The SCM process further defines the need to trace changes, and the ability to verify that the final delivered software has all of the planned enhancements that are supposed to be included in the release.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] It identifies four procedures that must be defined for each software project to ensure that a sound SCM process is implemented.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] These terms and definitions can change somewhat from standard to standard.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] ITIL specifies the use of a configuration management system (CMS) or configuration management database (CMDB) as a means of achieving industry best practices for Configuration Management.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] CMS helps manage a federated collection of CMDBs.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] The benefits of a CMS/CMDB includes being able to perform functions like root cause analysis, impact analysis, change management, and current state assessment for future state strategy development.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] For information assurance, CM can be defined as the management of security features and assurances through control of changes made to hardware, software, firmware, documentation, test, test fixtures, and test documentation throughout the life cycle of an information system.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] For example, configuration requirements may be different for a network firewall that functions as part of an organization's Internet boundary versus one that functions as an internal local network firewall.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] Configuration management is used to maintain an understanding of the status of complex assets with a view to maintaining the highest level of serviceability for the lowest cost.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] Specifically, it aims to ensure that operations are not disrupted due to the asset (or parts of the asset) overrunning limits of planned lifespan or below quality levels.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] In the military, this type of activity is often classed as "mission readiness", and seeks to define which assets are available and for which type of mission; a classic example is whether aircraft on board an aircraft carrier are equipped with bombs for ground support or missiles for defense.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] Configuration management can be used to maintain OS configuration files.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] Many of these systems utilize Infrastructure as Code to define and maintain configuration.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] The Promise theory of configuration maintenance was developed by Mark Burgess, with a practical implementation on present day computer systems in the software CFEngine able to perform real time repair as well as preventive maintenance.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] Understanding the "as is" state of an asset and its major components is an essential element in preventive maintenance as used in maintenance, repair, and overhaul and enterprise asset management systems.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] Complex assets such as aircraft, ships, industrial machinery etc. depend on many different components being serviceable.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] This serviceability is often defined in terms of the amount of usage the component has had since it was new, since fitted, since repaired, the amount of use it has had over its life and several other limiting factors.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] Understanding how near the end of their life each of these components is has been a major undertaking involving labor-intensive record keeping until recent developments in software.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] Many types of component use electronic sensors to capture data which provides live condition monitoring.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] This data is analyzed on board or at a remote location by computer to evaluate its current serviceability and increasingly its likely future state using algorithms which predict potential future failures based on previous examples of failure through field experience and modeling.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] This is the basis for "predictive maintenance".
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] Availability of accurate and timely data is essential in order for CM to provide operational value and a lack of this can often be a limiting factor.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] Capturing and disseminating the operating data to the various support organizations is becoming an industry in itself.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] The consumers of this data have grown more numerous and complex with the growth of programs offered by original equipment manufacturers (OEMs).
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] These are designed to offer operators guaranteed availability and make the picture more complex with the operator managing the asset but the OEM taking on the liability to ensure its serviceability.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] More recently configuration management has been applied to large construction projects which can often be very complex and have a huge number of details and changes that need to be documented.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] Construction agencies such as the Federal Highway Administration have used configuration management for their infrastructure projects.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] There are construction-based configuration management tools that aim to document change orders and RFIs in order to ensure a project stays on schedule and on budget.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] These programs can also store information to aid in the maintenance and modification of the infrastructure when it is completed.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/configuration-management] This study yielded results indicating a benefit to using configuration management on projects of this nature.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] The concept of managing infrastructure through code emerged from early configuration management practices.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] In the 1990s, tools such as CFEngine, created by Mark Burgess in 1993, introduced the idea of describing system configuration in a declarative language rather than executing manual commands, laying the intellectual groundwork for IaC.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] IaC emerged as organizations began managing larger and more complex infrastructure, particularly with the growth of cloud computing and the need to provision resources consistently and at scale.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] Treating infrastructure configuration like software - storing it in version control, reviewing it, and deploying it automatically allowed teams to reduce manual errors and reproduce environments reliably.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] The ability to treat infrastructure as code and use the same tools as any other software project would allow developers to rapidly deploy applications.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] The value of IaC can be broken down into three measurable categories: cost, speed, and risk.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] Cost reduction aims at helping not only the enterprise financially, but also in terms of people and effort, meaning that by removing the manual component, organizations are able to refocus their efforts on other enterprise tasks.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] Infrastructure automation enables speed through faster execution when configuring your infrastructure and provides visibility to help other teams across the enterprise work quickly and more efficiently.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] Automation removes the risk associated with human error, like manual misconfiguration; removing this can decrease downtime and increase reliability.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] These outcomes and attributes help the enterprise move toward implementing a culture of DevOps: the combined work of development and operations.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] There are generally two approaches to IaC: declarative (functional) vs. imperative (procedural).
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] The difference between the declarative and the imperative approach is essentially *what* versus *how*.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] The declarative approach focuses on what the eventual target configuration should be; the imperative focuses on how the infrastructure is to be changed to meet this.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] The declarative approach defines the desired state and the system executes what needs to happen to achieve that desired state.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] Imperative defines specific commands that need to be executed in the appropriate order to end with the desired conclusion.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] Infrastructure as Code (IaC) allows organizations to manage servers and their configurations using code.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] There are two ways to apply these configurations to servers: the 'push' and 'pull' methods.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] In the 'push' method, the system controlling the configuration directly sends instructions to the server.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] In the 'pull' method, the server retrieves its own instructions from the controlling system.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] There are many tools that fulfill infrastructure automation capabilities and use IaC.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] Broadly speaking, any framework or tool that performs changes or configures infrastructure declaratively or imperatively based on a programmatic approach can be considered IaC.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] Traditionally, server (lifecycle) automation and configuration management tools were used to accomplish IaC.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] Now enterprises are also using continuous configuration automation tools or stand-alone IaC frameworks, such as Microsoft’s PowerShell DSC or AWS CloudFormation.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] All continuous configuration automation (CCA) tools can be thought of as extensions of traditional IaC frameworks.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] They leverage IaC to change, configure, and automate infrastructure, and they also provide visibility, efficiency, and flexibility in how infrastructure is managed.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] These additional attributes provide enterprise-level security and compliance.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] Community content is a key determinant of an open-source CCA tool's quality.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] According to Gartner, the value of CCA tools is "as dependent on user-community-contributed content and support as it is on the commercial maturity and performance of the automation tooling".
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] Established vendors such as Puppet and Chef have created their own communities.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] Chef has Chef Community Repository and Puppet has PuppetForge.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] Other vendors rely on adjacent communities and leverage other IaC frameworks such as PowerShell DSC.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] New vendors are emerging that are not content-driven, but model-driven with the intelligence in the product to deliver content.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] These visual, object-oriented systems work well for developers, but they are especially useful to production-oriented DevOps and operations constituents that value models versus scripting for content.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] As the field continues to develop and change, the community-based content will become ever more important to how IaC tools are used, unless they are model-driven and object-oriented.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] Other tools include AWS CloudFormation, cdist, StackStorm, Juju, and Step CI.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] IaC can be a key attribute of enabling best practices in DevOps.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] Developers become more involved in defining configuration and Ops teams get involved earlier in the development process.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] Tools that utilize IaC bring visibility to the state and configuration of servers and ultimately provide the visibility to users within the enterprise, which brings teams together to maximize their efforts.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] Automation in general aims to take the confusion and error-prone aspect of manual processes and make it more efficient, and productive.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] Allowing for better software and applications to be created with flexibility, less downtime, and an overall cost-effective way for the company.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] IaC is intended to reduce the complexity that kills efficiency out of manual configuration.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] Automation and collaboration are considered central points in DevOps; infrastructure automation tools are often included as components of a DevOps toolchain.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/infrastructure-as-code] The 2020 Cloud Threat Report released by Unit 42 (the threat intelligence unit of cybersecurity provider Palo Alto Networks) identified around 200,000 potential vulnerabilities in infrastructure-as-code templates.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] In general, **compliance** means conforming to a rule, such as a specification, policy, standard or law.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] Compliance has traditionally been explained by reference to deterrence theory, according to which punishing a behavior will decrease the violations both by the wrongdoer (specific deterrence) and by others (general deterrence).
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] This view has been supported by economic theory, which has framed punishment in terms of costs and has explained compliance in terms of a cost-benefit equilibrium (Becker 1968).
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] However, psychological research on motivation provides an alternative view: granting rewards (Deci, Koestner and Ryan, 1999) or imposing fines (Gneezy Rustichini 2000) for a certain behavior is a form of extrinsic motivation that weakens intrinsic motivation and ultimately undermines compliance.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] Regulations and accrediting organizations vary among fields, with examples such as PCI-DSS and GLBA in the financial industry, FISMA for U.S. federal agencies, HACCP for the food and beverage industry, and the Joint Commission and HIPAA in healthcare.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] In some cases other compliance frameworks (such as COBIT) or even standards (NIST) inform on how to comply with regulations.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] Some organizations keep compliance data—all data belonging or pertaining to the enterprise or included in the law, which can be used for the purpose of implementing or validating compliance—in a separate store for meeting reporting requirements.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] Compliance software is increasingly being implemented to help companies manage their compliance data more efficiently.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] This store may include calculations, data transfers, and audit trails.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] The ISO also produces international standards such as ISO/IEC 27002 to help organizations meet regulatory compliance with their security management and assurance best practices.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] Some local or international specialized organizations such as the American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME) also develop standards and regulation codes.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] They thereby provide a wide range of rules and directives to ensure compliance of the products to safety, security or design standards.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] Regulatory compliance varies not only by industry but often by location.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] The financial, research, and pharmaceutical regulatory structures in one country, for example, may be similar but with particularly different nuances in another country.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] These similarities and differences are often a product "of reactions to the changing objectives and requirements in different countries, industries, and policy contexts".
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] These regulators help to ensure financial institutes meet their promises, that transactional information is well documented, and that competition is fair while protecting consumers.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] Australian organisations seeking to remain compliant with various regulations may turn to AS ISO 19600:2015 (which supersedes AS 3806-2006).
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] This standard helps organisations with compliance management, placing "emphasis on the organisational elements that are required to support compliance" while also recognizing the need for continual improvement.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] In Canada, federal regulation of deposits, insurance, and superannuation is governed by two independent bodies: the OSFI through the Bank Act, and FINTRAC, mandated by the Proceeds of Crime (Money Laundering) and Terrorist Financing Act, 2001 (PCMLTFA).
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] These groups protect consumers, regulate how risk is controlled and managed, and investigate illegal action such as money laundering and terrorist financing.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] On a provincial level, each province maintain individuals laws and agencies.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] Unlike any other major federation, Canada does not have a securities regulatory authority at the federal government level.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] The provincial and territorial regulators work together to coordinate and harmonize regulation of the Canadian capital markets through the Canadian Securities Administrators (CSA).
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] Other key regulators in Canada include the Canadian Food Inspection Agency (CFIA) for food safety, animal health, and plant health; Health Canada for public health; and Environment and Climate Change Canada for environment and sustainable energy.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] For more industry specific guidance, e.g., financial institutions, Canada's E-13 Regulatory Compliance Management provides specific compliance risk management tactics.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] Regulatory compliance in the European Union (EU) is governed by a harmonized legal framework designed to ensure consistency across member states while allowing for national implementation.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] EU compliance regulations cover various industries, including consumer product safety, financial services, environmental protection, and data privacy.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] The General Product Safety Regulation (GPSR) establishes a unified safety framework for consumer products across the EU, requiring manufacturers to conduct risk assessments, maintain traceability documentation, and meet safety compliance standards before placing products on the market.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] The GPSR applies to all consumer products made available in the EU unless covered by sector-specific regulations, such as medical devices or food products.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] The regulation extends to products sold through e-commerce platforms, requiring online marketplaces to ensure that only compliant products are listed.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] Fulfillment service providers are also included as economic operators, making them responsible for product safety compliance in certain cases.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] For business compliance, the EU’s regulatory approach is guided by the New Legislative Framework (NLF) and various sector-specific directives and regulations.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] Businesses must comply with EU product conformity assessments and affix the CE marking to indicate compliance with essential safety and performance standards.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] Financial compliance is enforced through regulations such as the Markets in Financial Instruments Directive (MiFID II) and the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which set strict requirements for financial transparency, consumer protection, and data security.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] The EU Legislation Compliance framework ensures that organizations operate within the legal boundaries of EU directives, helping public and private entities manage regulatory risks efficiently.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] Companies operating in the EU must stay updated on evolving compliance requirements, as non-compliance can lead to fines, product recalls, or restrictions on market access.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] The financial sector in the Netherlands is heavily regulated.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] The Dutch Central Bank (De Nederlandsche Bank N.V.) is the prudential regulator while the Netherlands Authority for Financial Markets (AFM) is the regulator for behavioral supervision of financial institutions and markets.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] In India, compliance regulation takes place across three strata: Central, State, and Local regulation.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] India veers towards central regulation, especially of financial organizations and foreign funds.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] Compliance regulations vary based on the industry segment in addition to the geographical mix.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] Most regulation comes in the following broad categories: economic regulation, regulation in the public interest, and environmental regulation.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] India has also been characterized by poor compliance - reports suggest that only around 65% of companies are fully compliant to norms.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] The Monetary Authority of Singapore is Singapore's central bank and financial regulatory authority.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] It administers the various statutes pertaining to money, banking, insurance, securities and the financial sector in general, as well as currency issuance.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] There is considerable regulation in the United Kingdom, some of which is derived from European Union legislation.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] Various areas are policed by different bodies, such as the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), Environment Agency, Scottish Environment Protection Agency, Information Commissioner's Office, Care Quality Commission, and others: see List of regulators in the United Kingdom.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] Important compliance issues for all organizations large and small include the Data Protection Act 2018 and, for the public sector, Freedom of Information Act 2000.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] Corporate scandals and breakdowns such as the Enron case of reputational risk in 2001 have increased calls for stronger compliance and regulations, particularly for publicly listed companies.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] The Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) is an agency of the United States Department of the Treasury under the auspices of the Under Secretary of the Treasury for Terrorism and Financial Intelligence.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] OFAC administers and enforces economic and trade sanctions based on U.S. foreign policy and national security goals against targeted foreign states, organizations, and individuals.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] Compliance in the U.S. generally means compliance with laws and regulations.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] These laws and regulations can have criminal or civil penalties.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] The definition of what constitutes an effective compliance plan has been elusive.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] Most authors, however, continue to cite the guidance provided by the United States Sentencing Commission in Chapter 8 of the Federal Sentencing Guidelines.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] Small Business Administration re-launched Business.gov (later Business.USA.gov and finally SBA.Gov) which provides a single point of access to government services and information that help businesses comply with government regulations.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] Department of Labor, Occupational Health and Safety Administration (OSHA) was created by Congress to assure safe and healthful working conditions for working men and women by setting and enforcing standards and by providing training, outreach, education, and assistance.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] OSHA implements laws and regulations regularly in the following areas, construction, maritime, agriculture, and recordkeeping.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] The United States Department of Transportation also has various laws and regulations requiring that prime contractors when bidding on federally funded projects engage in good faith effort compliance, meaning they must document their outreach to certified disadvantaged business enterprises.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] Data retention is a part of regulatory compliance that is proving to be a challenge in many instances.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] The security that comes from compliance with industry regulations can seem contrary to maintaining user privacy.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] Data retention laws and regulations ask data owners and other service providers to retain extensive records of user activity beyond the time necessary for normal business operations.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] These requirements have been called into question by privacy rights advocates.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] Compliance in this area is becoming very difficult.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] Laws like the CAN-SPAM Act and Fair Credit Reporting Act in the U.S. require that businesses give people the right to be forgotten.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] In other words, they must remove individuals from marketing lists if it is requested, tell them when and why they might share personal information with a third party, or at least ask permission before sharing that data.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] Now, with new laws coming out that demand longer data retention despite the individual’s desires, it can create some real difficulties.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] Money laundering and terrorist financing pose significant threats to the integrity of the financial system and national security.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] To combat these threats, the EU has adopted a risk-based approach to Anti-Money Laundering and Combating the Financing of Terrorism (AML/CFT) that relies on cooperation and coordination between EU and national authorities.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] In this context, risk-based regulation refers to the approach of identifying and assessing potential risks of money laundering and terrorist financing and implementing regulatory measures proportional to those risks.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] However, the shared enforcement powers between EU and national authorities in the implementation and enforcement of AML/CFT regulations can create legal implications and challenges.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] The potential for inconsistent application of AML regulations across different jurisdictions can create regulatory arbitrage and undermine the effectiveness of AML efforts.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] Additionally, a lack of clear and consistent legal frameworks defining the roles and responsibilities of EU and national authorities in AML enforcement can lead to situations where accountability is difficult to establish.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] Corporate Governance Code (formerly the Combined Code) is issued by the Financial Reporting Council (FRC) and "sets standards of good practice in relation to board leadership and effectiveness, remuneration, accountability, and relations with shareholders".
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] All companies with a Premium Listing of equity shares in the U.K. are required under the Listing Rules to report on how they have applied the Combined Code in their annual report and accounts.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] It further demonstrates the relationship that subsists among shareholders, management, and the independent audit teams.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] Financial statements must be prepared using a particular set of rules and regulations hence the rationale behind allowing the companies to apply the provisions of company law, international financial reporting standards (IFRS), as well as the U.K. stock exchange rules as directed by the FCA.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/regulatory-compliance] It is also possible that shareholders may not understand the figures as presented in the various financial statements, hence it is critical that the board should provide notes on accounting policies as well as other explanatory notes to help them understand the report better.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/security-controls] Systems of controls can be referred to as frameworks or standards.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/security-controls] Frameworks can enable an organization to manage security controls across different types of assets with consistency.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/security-controls] Security controls are to help reduce the likelihood or any impacts of security incidents and protect the CIA triad for the systems and the data.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/security-controls] While protecting it helps organizations meet its responsibilities; consistent risk management to systems, assets, data, networks and physical infrastructures.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/security-controls] Security controls can be classified by various criteria.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/security-controls] These classifications help organizations build a well designed multi-layered defense strategy, ensuring that they layers help control and prevent when threats are being taken placed.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/security-controls] Security controls include both technical controls (such as access management and fire walls) and administrative controls (including policies and procedures).
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/security-controls] Controls are part of risk treatment strategy which is applied after risk assessment and then design, building, operating, and changing them is a part of the lifecycle.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/security-controls] The **ISO/IEC 27000 series** standards promote good security practices and define frameworks or systems to structure the analysis and design for managing information security controls.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/security-controls] Most recent version, ISO/IEC 27001;2022, released in October 2022, specifies 93 controls organized some of the most well known standards are outlined below.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/security-controls] All organizations certified to ISO 27001:2013 are obliged to transition to the new version of the Standard within 3 years (by October 2025).
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/security-controls] The Federal Information Processing Standards (FIPS) apply to all US government agencies.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/security-controls] However, certain national security systems, under the purview of the Committee on National Security Systems, are managed outside these standards.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/security-controls] A maturity based framework divided into five functional areas and approximately 100 individual controls in its "core" and is widely used by U.S. organizations and government agencies.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/security-controls] A database of nearly one thousand technical controls grouped into families and cross references.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/security-controls] A proprietary control set published by ISACA.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/security-controls] Formerly known as the SANS Critical Security Controls now officially called the CIS Critical Security Controls (COS Controls).
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/security-controls] The CIS Controls are divided into 18 prioritized cybersecurity best practices that protect systems and data from threats.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/security-controls] The Controls are divided further into Implementation Groups (IGs) which are a recommended guidance to prioritize implementation of the CIS controls.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/security-controls] The intersection of security risk and laws that set standards of care is where data liability are defined.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/security-controls] A handful of databases are emerging to help risk managers research laws that define liability at the country, province/state, and local levels.
[src:cloud-security-posture-deep/security-controls] In these control sets, compliance with relevant laws are the actual risk mitigators.
